She dances in a foul gloom where gum bums with garlic. A sailorman, rustbearded, sips
               from a beaker rum and eyes her. A long and seafed silent rut. She dances, capers,
               wagging her sowish haunches and her hips, on her gross belly flapping a ruby egg.

The reverend Hugh C. Love walked
               from the old chapterhouse of saint Mary’s abbey past James and Charles Kennedy’s,
               rectifiers, attended by Geraldines tall and personable,
